content.text:
This is a big architectural question. Let me synthesize what I learned from the research.

## The Core Tension

Managed Agents has **no built-in browser/computer-use tool**. Its toolset is: `bash`, `read`, `write`, `edit`, `glob`, `grep`, `web_fetch`, `web_search`. The current Stagehand CUA architecture is fundamentally a screenshot-based loop using the `computer` tool — that doesn't exist in managed agents.

So the migration isn't "swap the API" — it's a rearchitecture of how browser capabilities are exposed to Claude.

## Two Viable Approaches

### Option A: Custom Tools (simplest)

Define Stagehand primitives as custom tools the managed agent calls. Your service handles `agent.custom_tool_use` events, executes against the browser, and returns results.

```
Managed Agent (Anthropic-hosted loop)
  ├─ Thinks & plans autonomously
  ├─ Calls custom tool: browse_navigate({ url })
  │   → you execute via Stagehand, return screenshot + status
  ├─ Calls custom tool: browse_act({ instruction: "click sign in" })
  │   → you run stagehand.act(), return screenshot
  ├─ Calls custom tool: browse_extract({ instruction, schema })
  │   → you run stagehand.extract(), return structured data
  └─ Calls custom tool: browse_observe({ instruction })
      → you run stagehand.observe(), return candidate actions
```

The agent definition would look something like:

```typescript
const agent = await anthropic.agents.create({
  name: "chromie",
  model: { id: "claude-opus-4-6" },
  instructions: "You are a browser automation agent. Use the browse_* tools to interact with web pages...",
  tools: [
    {
      type: "custom",
      name: "browse_navigate",
      description: "Navigate to a URL. Returns a screenshot of the page.",
      input_schema: {
        type: "object",
        properties: { url: { type: "string" } },
        required: ["url"],
      },
    },
    {
      type: "custom",
      name: "browse_act",
      description: "Perform an atomic action on the current page (click, type, etc). Returns a screenshot after the action.",
      input_schema: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
          instruction: { type: "string" },
          page_index: { type: "number" },
        },
        required: ["instruction"],
      },
    },
    {
      type: "custom",
      name: "browse_extract",
      description: "Extract structured data from the current page.",
      input_schema: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
          instruction: { type: "string" },
          schema: { type: "object" },
        },
        required: ["instruction"],
      },
    },
    {
      type: "custom",
      name: "browse_screenshot",
      description: "Take a screenshot of the current page.",
      input_schema: { type: "object", properties: {} },
    },
  ],
});
```

Client-side event loop:

```typescript
const session = await anthropic.sessions.create({
  agent_id: agent.id,
  environment_id: env.id,
});

// Open SSE stream
const stream = await anthropic.sessions.stream(session.id);

// Send instruction
await anthropic.sessions.events.create(session.id, {
  type: "user.message",
  content: { text: "Go to github.com and star the stagehand repo" },
});

// Handle events
for await (const event of stream) {
  if (event.type === "agent.custom_tool_use") {
    const { name, input, id } = event;

    let result;
    switch (name) {
      case "browse_navigate":
        await page.goto(input.url);
        const screenshot = await page.screenshot({ encoding: "base64" });
        result = { url: page.url(), screenshot };
        break;
      case "browse_act":
        await stagehand.act(input.instruction);
        const ss = await page.screenshot({ encoding: "base64" });
        result = { success: true, screenshot: ss };
        break;
      case "browse_extract":
        const data = await stagehand.extract(input.instruction);
        result = { data };
        break;
      // ...
    }

    await anthropic.sessions.events.create(session.id, {
      type: "user.custom_tool_result",
      event_id: id,
      content: JSON.stringify(result),
    });
  }

  if (event.type === "session.status_idle" && event.stop_reason === "end_turn") {
    break;
  }
}
```

### Option B: MCP Server (cleaner long-term)

Expose Stagehand/Browserbase as an MCP server. The managed agent connects to it directly — no custom tool handling needed on your side.

```typescript
const agent = await anthropic.agents.create({
  name: "chromie",
  model: { id: "claude-opus-4-6" },
  instructions: "You are a browser automation agent...",
  tools: [
    {
      type: "mcp_toolset",
      mcp_server_name: "browserbase",
      // Anthropic handles calling the MCP server directly
    },
  ],
  mcp_servers: [
    {
      name: "browserbase",
      url: "https://mcp.browserbase.com",  // or wherever it's hosted
    },
  ],
});
```

This is cleaner because Anthropic's harness calls the MCP server directly — your client code is just sending messages and reading events. But it requires Browserbase to run a publicly accessible MCP server.

## What You Lose vs. Current Architecture

| Current (client-side loop) | Managed Agents |
|---|---|
| Full control over each step | Anthropic controls the loop |
| Raw `computer` tool with coordinates | No coordinate-based actions; use Stagehand's DOM-based `act`/`observe` instead |
| Custom image compression between steps | Anthropic handles context management |
| `preStepHook` for captcha solving | Would need to be a custom tool or built into the action handler |
| Per-step logging via FlowLogger | Span events (`span.model_request_start/end`) give token-level observability |
| `observe → act` caching pattern | Agent decides tool order autonomously |
| Multi-provider support (OpenAI, Google, Microsoft CUA) | Anthropic models only |

## What You Gain

- **No agent loop code** — Anthropic manages retries, context compaction, prompt caching
- **Session persistence** — resume from where you left off, event replay
- **60% lower TTFT** (per their benchmarks)
- **Built-in `web_search`/`web_fetch`** — agent can research without browser
- **Multi-agent orchestration** (research preview) — chromie could be one of several callable agents
- **Skills system** — package browser automation patterns as reusable skills

## My Recommendation

**Option A (custom tools)** is the pragmatic starting point. It maps cleanly to Stagehand's existing `act`/`extract`/`observe` primitives, keeps Browserbase infrastructure unchanged, and lets you validate the managed agents value prop (loop management, caching, context compaction) before committing to a deeper MCP integration.

The key architectural shift is: instead of sending raw screenshots + coordinate-based `computer` tool actions, you'd expose Stagehand's higher-level DOM-based methods as the tool interface. This is actually arguably better — the managed agent reasons about *what* to do, and Stagehand handles *how* to do it.

Want me to spike out a proof-of-concept implementation of either approach?
